2. Project Objective
The main objective of this project was to design and implement an AI-driven phishing website
detection system. PhishGuard aims to analyze any given URL in real time and classify it as “Safe”
or “Malicious”. Given that phishing is one of the most common and dangerous cybersecurity
threats, the system is intended to help users make safer browsing decisions by automatically
identifying deceptive or harmful sites.
3. Project description (Detailed)
PhishGuard is a machine learning–powered web application developed to detect phishing
websites by analyzing various URL-based features. The project was executed in multiple phases,
from initial problem understanding through final deployment. Initially, a dataset containing both
legitimate and malicious URLs was collected and studied. Data preprocessing was applied – for
example, removing duplicate entries, handling missing or malformed values, and normalizing
URL strings – to improve data quality.
Next, feature extraction converted each URL into a set of numerical features. Common URLbased features were extracted, such as the total URL length, hostname length, number of dots,
and other structural attributes. For example, very long URLs or those containing an IP address
instead of a domain name are often indicative of phishing. The features also included the
presence of HTTPS, the count of suspicious keywords (e.g. “login”, “verify”), and the domain age
(newly-registered domains are often used by attackers).
After feature engineering, multiple machine learning models were trained and evaluated.
Classifiers such as Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, Random Forest, and XGBoost were
compared using metrics like accuracy, precision, and recall. In our experiments, XGBoost
consistently provided the best classification performance and handled feature interactions
robustly, so it was selected as the final model. The trained model was serialized (saved) for
deployment in the next phase.
The trained model was integrated into a Flask-based REST API. This API accepts a usersubmitted URL, applies the same feature extraction steps in real time, and uses the model to
predict whether the URL is safe or malicious. The prediction result (along with a confidence
score) is returned to the client in JSON format. Finally, a responsive web front end was
developed to allow users to enter URLs and view the results. The interface supports user login
and maintains a history of scanned URLs for each user, making the application more practical
and user-friendly.

