The project was executed using a structured, phase-by-phase approach. The initial phase
focused on understanding phishing attack patterns and studying how malicious URLs differ from
legitimate ones. Based on this analysis, relevant datasets containing phishing and legitimate
URLs were collected from trusted sources.
During the data preprocessing phase, the raw URL dataset was cleaned by removing duplicate
entries, invalid or corrupted URLs, and missing values. URL formats were normalized to ensure
consistency across the dataset, which helped improve the reliability of feature extraction and
model training.
Feature engineering played a crucial role in the system’s performance. Each URL was parsed to
extract meaningful features such as URL length, number of dots, presence of an IP address,
usage of HTTPS, suspicious keywords, and domain age. For example, URLs containing IP
addresses or newly registered domains are commonly associated with phishing attacks. These
extracted attributes were combined into numerical feature vectors suitable for machine learning
models.
After feature extraction, the dataset was split into training and testing sets using a 70:30 ratio.
Multiple machine learning classifiers were trained on the training data and evaluated using the
testing data. Based on performance metrics such as accuracy and consistency, XGBoost
emerged as the best-performing classifier. The final trained model was serialized and deployed
using a Flask-based REST API, which accepts URLs as input, performs feature extraction, and
returns prediction results in JSON format.
On the frontend, a web-based user interface was developed using React (HTML, CSS, and
JavaScript). The interface allows users to enter a URL and submit it for analysis. The request is
first sent to a Node.js and Express-based backend server, which acts as an intermediary layer
between the frontend and the machine learning model.
The Node/Express backend forwards the submitted URL to the Flask-based machine learning
API for prediction. After receiving the classification result, the backend sends the response back
to the frontend. The user interface then displays the result (e.g., “Malicious URL Detected”), along
with a confidence score and a simple risk indicator for better user understanding.
User authentication was implemented to allow users to securely log in and access their personal
scan history. All system components were thoroughly tested, including frontend form submission,
backend request handling, and communication with the Flask API. This ensured smooth and
reliable interaction between the React frontend, Node/Express backend, and Flask-based
machine learning service..
