6. Machine Learning Workflow
The ML workflow for PhishGuard followed these steps:
1. Data Collection and Exploration: Gather a labeled dataset of legitimate and
phishing URLs and perform initial analysis.
2. Data Cleaning and Preprocessing: Clean the data by removing duplicates,
correcting formats, and normalizing text.
3. Feature Extraction: Compute features for each URL (length, number of special
characters, domain properties, etc.).
4. Train-Test Split: Divide the dataset ( 70% training, 30% testing) to evaluate
model performance on unseen data.
5. Model Training: Train multiple classifiers (Logistic Regression, Random Forest,
XGBoost) on the training data, tuning hyperparameters via grid search.
6. Model Evaluation: Measure each model’s accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-
score on the test set.
7. Model Selection: Choose XGBoost for deployment, as it yielded the highest
accuracy and robustness.
8. Model Deployment: Serialize the chosen model and load it in the Flask API for
real-time predictions.
7. Feature Extraction
The following URL-based features were engineered:
• URL Length: Total number of characters in the URL. Extremely long URLs can
indicate obfuscation by attackers.
• Hostname Length: Number of characters in the domain/hostname part.
Unusually long hostnames may be suspicious.
• Number of Dots: Count of . characters in the URL. A high number can indicate
many subdomains or IP usage.
• Presence of HTTPS: Boolean indicating if the URL uses https://. Legitimate sites
typically use HTTPS.
• Presence of IP Address: Boolean indicating if the URL uses an IP address
instead of a domain name (often seen in phishing links).
Suspicious Keywords: Count of known phishing-related keywords in the URL
(e.g. “login”, “secure”, “bank”). Phishing URLs often include such terms to appear
credible.
• Domain Age: Age of the domain in days (from WHOIS data). Newly-registered
domains are commonly used in phishing.
These features are well-known heuristics in phishing detection. Each URL in the dataset
was converted into a feature vector using this set.
8. Model Training and Evaluation
Several classifiers were trained on the extracted features, including Logistic Regression,
Decision Tree, Random Forest, and XGBoost. Each model’s predictions were evaluated
on the test set using accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. Cross-validation was
used to tune hyperparameters (e.g. adjusting tree depth and learning rate).
XGBoost stood out with the best performance, consistent with published results. Its
ability to combine many weak learners into a strong classifier made it well-suited to our
feature set.
The final XGBoost model was serialized (for example, saved with joblib) so that it could
be loaded by the backend service. This trained model now powers the real-time
predictions. During evaluation, confusion matrices confirmed that both phishing and
benign URLs were identified correctly, with a low false positive and false negative rate.
9. Backend API Development
The backend was implemented as a RESTful API using Flask. Key components include:
• Prediction Endpoint: An endpoint ( /predict) that accepts a URL in an HTTP
request. When called, the server:
1. Extracts features from the URL using the same preprocessing logic.
2. Loads the trained XGBoost model and performs a prediction.
3. Returns the result and confidence score in JSON format (e.g.
{"prediction": "Malicious", "confidence": 0.92}).
• User Management: Endpoints for user signup, login, and logout. Secure
password hashing and session handling protect user accounts.

• Scan History: Endpoints to save and retrieve each user’s scan history in a
database. This allows the frontend to display past results to the user.
Input validation and error handling were implemented to ensure robustness (e.g.
verifying valid URL format). The Flask API was tested (using tools like Postman) to
confirm that requests are processed correctly and responses are returned as expected.

10. Frontend Development
A responsive and user-friendly web interface was developed to enable users to
interact with the PhishGuard system. The frontend was implemented using React, along
with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, to ensure a dynamic and interactive user experience
across different devices.
The main functionalities of the frontend include:
• URL Submission:
The interface provides a text input field and submit button that allow users to
enter a website URL for analysis. Client-side input validation is performed to
ensure the correctness of the URL format before submission.
• Result Display:
After the URL is analyzed, the frontend displays the classification result, clearly
indicating whether the website is “Safe” or “Malicious.” The prediction is
accompanied by a confidence score and a simple visual risk indicator to improve
user understanding.
• User Authentication:
Dedicated pages for user registration and login were implemented. Secure
session management ensures that only authenticated users can access
protected features such as scan history.
• Scan History Dashboard:
Logged-in users can access a personalized dashboard displaying previously
scanned URLs along with their corresponding prediction results. This information
is securely fetched from the backend server.
The user interface design emphasizes clarity, simplicity, and usability.
Asynchronous API communication was implemented using Axios, allowing the
frontend to interact efficiently with the Node.js/Express backend and the Flask-based
machine learning API without requiring full page reloads. After development, the
frontend was integrated and tested with the backend services to ensure seamless data
flow and a smooth overall user experience. 
11. Challenges Faced
During the development of the PhishGuard system, several technical and
implementation challenges were encountered, particularly due to the integration of a
MERN stack application with a machine learning service.
• Feature Engineering:
Identifying the most relevant URL-based features for phishing detection required
extensive research and experimentation. Selecting effective suspicious keywords
and determining meaningful attributes such as domain age and URL structure
involved multiple iterations and validation steps.
• Machine Learning Model Integration:
Integrating the trained machine learning model with the web application was
challenging. Ensuring consistency between the feature extraction process used
during training and the real-time prediction pipeline in the Flask API required
careful serialization and testing.
• MERN Stack and ML Service Communication:
Establishing reliable communication between the React frontend, Node.js and
Express backend, and the Flask-based machine learning API was a key
challenge. Proper request handling, response formatting, and error management
were implemented to ensure smooth data flow across services.
• Deployment and Performance Issues:
Deploying the Flask ML API alongside the Node/Express backend required
managing dependencies, server configurations, and performance optimization.
Handling concurrent requests and maintaining low response latency for real-time
predictions was also a challenge.
• Authentication and Database Management:
Implementing secure user authentication and managing persistent scan history
using MongoDB added complexity. Ensuring secure password storage through
hashing and maintaining data integrity across user sessions required careful
backend design.
These challenges were addressed through systematic testing, debugging, and
iterative development. Unit testing was used to verify individual components such as
feature extraction and model inference, while integration testing ensured smooth end-toend functionality across the MERN stack and machine learning service.

